<DOC><DOCNO> AP880413-0265 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 0257EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   04-13 0526</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0550</SECOND><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Financially ailing First RepublicBank Corp.expects to post a $1.5 billion loss in the first quarter, and saysits chairman has resigned as part of a management shakeup arrangedby federal regulators.   The projected loss disclosed Tuesday was attributed to a 50percent increase in the company's loan-loss provision, to $231million, and writedowns from foreclosed properties, all totaling$1.5 billion.   First RepublicBank also said Gerald W. Fronterhouse resigned asbank chief executive and chairman as part of a management shakeuparranged by federal regulators overseeing recapitalization of thecompany.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co. says Vice Chairman Harold A.Poling earned nearly $11 million during 1987 in salary, bonuses andexercised stock options.   The company disclosed Tuesday that Poling earned $808,697 insalary, $2 million in bonuses and $8,060,272 in exercising stockoptions.   Ford Chairman Donald E. Petersen, who exercised no optionsduring 1987, earned $2.8 million in bonuses and $929,934 in salary,according to the proxy, which was mailed to Ford's 265,000shareholders.   In all, the statement said the company paid $247.9 million inbonuses to 5,166 executives. That works out to an average of nearly$48,000 apiece.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of Allegis Corp. has a contract thatpays $575,000 per year with a bonus worth more than $6 million toreplace valuable stock options he held previously at TigerInternational Inc., documents show.   Under the Allegis stock appreciation plan, after Aug. 8.,Stephen M. Wolf has the right to be paid the difference between themarket price of 590,000 Tiger International shares and $3.32,according to documents filed with the Securities and ExchangeCommission.   Tiger International closed Tuesday at $14.75 on the New YorkStock Exchange, so the deal is currently worth $6.7 million.</TEXT><DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Loss-plagued Lorimar TelepicturesCorp., a major producer of television programming, has called offmerger talks with Warner Communications Corp.   Lorimar's one-sentence announcement Tuesday offered noexplanation for cancellation of discussions that began early inMarch with a buyout offer from the New York-based entertainmentconglomerate. Lorimar spokeswoman Sue Binford said the companywouldn't elaborate.   Warner spokesman Geoffrey Holmes declined to say why the talksfell through or what Warner had been willing to offer.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Northeastern states with high levels of publicspending have the most vital economies while ``low wage, low tax''states in the South, Plains and Mountain regions have the worst, aprivate research organization says.   The Corporation for Enterprise Development released an economicreport card Tuesday that listed six states as leaders in theeconomic competition between the states. They are Connecticut,Maryland, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Vermont and Minnesota.</TEXT><DATELINE>EVERETT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Boeing officials are defending their jetsagainst complaints from at least three airlines that said thewidebody series of 747s and 767s had serious quality-controlproblems.   Phil Condit, executive vice president for Boeing CommericalAirplanes, said Tuesday the recent publicity about the complaintswas due partly to the company's open way of dealing with itsproblems, which has made many workers aware of items that needimproving.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>